ent with this research. The authors examine the ways in which rural elders are connected to community and place, the contributions they make to family and neighbours, and the organisations and groups to which they belong. Highly topical issues around later life explored through these perspectives include older people’s financial security, leisure, access to services, transport and mobility, civic engagement and digital inclusion – all considered within the rural context in an era of fiscal austerity. In doing so, this book challenges problem-based views of ageing rural populations through considering barriers and facilitators to older people’s inclusion and opportunities for community participation in rural settings. Countryside Connections is a valuable text for students, researchers and practitioners with interests in rural ageing, civic engagement and interdisciplinary methods, theory and practice.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aOlder peoplezGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Gerontology.2bisacsh1 aBailey, Jane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiggs, Iain, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurholt, Vanessa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurholt, Vanessa, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBuzzo, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCurry, Nigel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDoheny, Shane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEales, Jacquie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEvans, Simon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalvin, Kathleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 